A Republican Strategy to Bway Obama's Re-Election
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers this to be a myth and states that electoral fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people who die from the fall of lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is true: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In that regard, these measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And in the same vein, a majority of American governments have enacted, since 2009, new laws that make it difficult for the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread following the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to submit an identity document with a photograph, in addition to an American citizenship test.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of scrutiny and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit an identity document with photography.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana law.
That is why the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo identity document.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo identity documents issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity card costs more than a hundred dollars.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people who earn less than $35,000 per year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have a photo identity card.
And there's still more.
In many states students, electors who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo identity document issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who often vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required a citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, the Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to assist voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in the rate of registration of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favoured the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter represented only 13 per cent of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the exact same thing happened.
They represent only 11 per cent of the voters, which is equal to 24 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, which account for 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Public Prosecutor & apos; s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law that required the submission of an identity document with photography.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in the key states.
A report from the Brennan Centre in 2011 shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty whether these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is true: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In this regard, the measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
