The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it's not entirely clear that it's Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it is much like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are still missing to be completely secure.
However, we assume that this is about Higgs, as the chances of being wrong seem to be few. We will see what this is about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because it will end up getting hurt.
Although the physics of the particles is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the principle of the exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physics classify the particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we meet the good citizens called fermiones, who are wise to obey at the beginning of Pauli.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not speak here, and the "force particles," by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it could be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave is born (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons "carrying force."
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is about another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "messy" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is far more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it takes extremely high energies, a little as if it were an ice-cream pond in which only a thick rock could slide down the surface.
This is why a huge particle accelerator such as CERN (the great Hadron collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do do have a mass, while the rest (as the photon, by the way) do not.
But what "can they bring" all these investigations, asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to vote on the differences between observations and predictions of MS.
For their part, many fervently want them to be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, such as that it does not propose any explanation concerning gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of such research on our day-to-day is difficult to predict, but we do not think we are wrong to say that it will have none.
For you to see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution that their work would provoke.
They were interviewing scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle said, who worked at Bell's laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who produced the first continuous laser (the first were pressed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory device."
Imagine...
And also, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself produced a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not at all its original intention, this captor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which was worth the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
