It is nothing impressive if we compare it to global changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual coins such as "credits," used to advance in a video game and that can be won by playing or can be bought (and even at times exchanged).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and treats changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both accountancy book depositaries, verifiers, currency emitters, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes are recorded in the public account book, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add that complementary line.
This is a process of file chopping, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical print.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "chopping" the set.
The aim is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would become orphan, as both have different prints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, likely by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the ninetieth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the power of calculation.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The failure used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes account of the potential for money-laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same defect.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, like the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Insite in Israel, analyzed the book of accounting and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "giant rebates" were launched.
"$30,000 was changed," Jon Holmquist rejoices, who works for Coinabul, who turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile non-contact payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to put into operation in the shops, which do not have to install new terminals or softwars.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to review hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to impose, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
In addition, in its report the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, in the event that this currency is successful.
