A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which gives it provisional full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given that Assembly another two months to complete its work.
And Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times modified, for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial havoc.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persevere in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "betraying his word" and "trampling on the right."
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a step towards a faster end to the institutional and political crisis and an acceleration of the transition process.
A referendum should be organized in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to recover a popular and democratic legitimization while the controversial causes havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Since this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either my text is voted on or I maintain full powers," powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, the vast majority of them Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be achieved, 11 people, replacement members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As was to be expected, the articles voted on had been unanimously.
The fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed almost at the time of prayer is funny to the commentators, on the other hand, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all the views, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law was a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules," which would have made it possible to apply more strictly.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals have made him hypocrisy and believe that it is nothing more than an advertising ruse.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who is to confirm its conformity with the laws of the Sharia.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing that "people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy. "
The fears of the liberals are also increased by the fact that the next rector of the university would be quite less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil status.
Most jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university, some of them formed in the French system, "explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But it recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic case law, ndlr].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule above all this. "
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday received many criticisms concerning the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflictive point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the desire of the military, the review of the defence budget shall not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, the insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
