What can this project actually bring? What do you think the conclusions are?
It is precisely a common control of this kind that could help us to stop investing efforts in the implementation of laws, the reduction and the improvement of limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
The savings economy means to get a thing right at a reasonable price (which does not always mean that the price is the lowest) in order to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But not by reducing the limit of awards means that we are going to make it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much "paperwork," that those who want to look for system failures will be able to do it more easily than if the limits were kept as high as now.
You are talking about the problems of our country with the transfer of the legislation governing the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized otherwise?
As for the offices, such as the NKU, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with a similar organization to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also to some extent analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of accounts are even at this level, in this respect slightly different from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which we call state funds here.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to establish a comparison without concrete data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be precise what it is best for.
Could it be better, for example, as regards the quality of the inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make this kind of comparison.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If not, it would be no benefit for them to work with our office, wouldn't it?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Is it in any way manifest its impact?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been expressed in the control proceedings.
As we carry out ex post controls, there is a need for some delay.
For the time being, it is noted in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks," through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of the selection process and similar are rectified.
Do you think that the adoption of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is probably a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that may arise is that the rules "tighten" and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each unrespected law on public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so in this way.
The system should exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path is taking us.
