Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in just under a month the end of the world will come, what do you think about it?
It's just one of so many other alarmist news that we like to hold on to.
The Tap Tap music group rather likes to make jokes about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that can gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you organized a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
This is a state-owned charity that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar set for December 21 at 11: 10 in the morning.
The day before, on December 20 at 21: 00, we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at about the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on Kiribati Island, in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
It was initially my idea, then we were all building the project together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of articles: boots, T-shirts, bags and original keyboards against the end of the world that can be acquired at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap group, together with other interpreters, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is entitled "End of the world, cancelled."
It is currently very popular on YouTube, can you hear it at the charity concerts?
Of course it is, and it will be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
It will be sung by all the interpreters at the same time at the three concerts.
The hymns will link together simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the video clip, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We work together even with other personalities from the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charitable events and concerts...
We make every effort to participate in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and have fun working with us.
What will the money raised at the concerts against the end of the world be allocated to?
To equipment for the school without barriers Studeo, we have completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
The students of the Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they carry out fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we make an effort to make it possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be an independent building to which we will move with this project.
A number of groups and interpreters are present at each concert.
What are the selection criteria?
We are trying to develop a programme that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague they will perform Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
For more detailed information, please consult www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar "spectacular action" planned in the future?
In May we will be performing for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I personally, taking advantage that we are in the United States, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not precisely minimalists, so far you have acted for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group of persons with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as hard as it can look at first sight.
There are five members in electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which still surprises me.
Even in Moscow, where we have recently returned, everything came out smoothly.
Through the exits abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you met so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still not common for a person to travel alone through the city center in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, there it is not.
Luckily, a civil association had been established that was working to tematise the problems of persons with disabilities.
In what aspects should we take the example of more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we're going through behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people to whom it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a serious disability to move on their own in public and to be able to go to the service, the museum, wherever you want...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate actively in social life, in this regard, with The Tap Tap we are a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers will start to change everything really.
So far, they are isolated cases of people who have a great force of will.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if we look a few years ago, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered as an educator in Jedličkův ústav, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to engage in something.
And since I'm a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Láņa Angelovič says, we got a little out of hand (laughter).
However, popularity did not come until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that we were quite helped by connecting with famous singers and also working actively to promote the group.
We come to the conclusion that the work that is not seen, is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to the support of the European Union, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to get that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that you can do something else.
The world of show is full of things that look like each other.
It is logical, in its own way, that everything new is welcomed with caution and takes a long time to accept.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and of whom we must have compassion.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop, on the condition, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it's not just a step forward for them, but for the whole society.
Did the fact that you are a demanding boss, as many people describe you, help?
If we want to do a job of quality, we have to be rigorous in many ways and demand a certain discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and with their heads in the clouds and when they find out they have to go two days to rehearse, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and at concerts, the initial euphoria quickly abandons them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and get something.
The Tap Tap group currently has twenty members.
How many of them were already in the beginning of 1998?
Just one: Láł a Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come in and out, you can't help it.
