Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, where, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of the cosmonautics, known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
In 1925, a dresin was built in Poland and was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal was not known, nor were the project's highlights known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dresin or for its braking.
The information about this dresin is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to engage in missiles.
The research was funded by the Komorka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with the prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietopuerto lotnicza," by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile techniques projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies on the cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine problemy, reference is made for the first time to the society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, of Prof. M. Subotowicze, he proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to the cosmonautics.
By that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) had been seeking to become part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became the Vice President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the MRI (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and air tests of the RM-2 two-stage rockets in the Błędów desert began in summer 1959.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which were different from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum apogee in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was later built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined in the research of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social trade law.
The resolution aroused a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the existing problem from a broader point of view.
The liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic and less regulatory competition.
This therefore means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (of wages) leads to economic tensions.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so "causes a fall" in the competitor's price with the aim of getting the majority of the market and thus increase its profit margin.
On a large scale, for most employers, it means moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and thus is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the state's social expenditure necessarily increases.
This whole situation is conducive to the total lack of interest of employers in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their pursuit of profit.
The situation is so universally known that there is no need for specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the Governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account social decline.
This is particularly evident in the changes to existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictate of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the limited right of employees to labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with the widening gap between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years now, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid already reaches a million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly common case: people employed on such low wages that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of almost all the states of the south of the EU certainly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to migrate as in the 19th century or to be malnourished with a terrible wage on the edge of society, in the hope that one day they will reach the private investment capital country.
Do you have to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, poverty then goes from country to country or never comes, as Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African continue to work for a small part of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media say to the satisfaction that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that leading the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence the political march and, therefore, the entire state with its selfishness.
In this case the answer is clearly yes.
The test is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that is manifested in the area of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is almost unlikely everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, charge the drafting of bills to private legal companies, which are often linked to industry.
These types of bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that the democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation like the one that Appiános describes in his work The crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompeya: "The state had been disintegrating for a long time and the administrations were working hard."
In exchange for bribes, illegally obtained favors and help to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread without any impediment and people went to the polls with the vote beaten in advance... "" there were no people with a character who would aspire to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls... "" He began to speak seriously that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose a strong man... "Although Appiános thought of Pompeya, Caesar came to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, just as in old times, is that today's society is based on unconsidered preferences of individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not, in its essence, able to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal-type democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The really devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands in lives, social and humanitarian disasters that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the law on public procurement is not the solution, at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at the international level and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
