Argo Movie: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a group of Islamist students occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive perspective: throwing the shah overboard could not be allowed, since, if it did, it would jeopardize the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later intensified further with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the negotiating intervention of the Algerian government.
In the US, its fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck tempered an episode of this story, which made a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated break, they ended up at the Canadian embassy residence.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping a hidden story an extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the shooting of a science fiction superproduction.
Gender combination
The plan drawn up by the "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized journals, press conferences were organized, the fictitious production society even had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
The Affleck film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper motion," the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film, the mood is combined. On the one hand, we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits, we show emblematic photographs of the time of the events, which were made in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this respect.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from the CIA and other institutions: men brought in who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has no longer been the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Adios mino, Adios" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Robbers" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where it was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "runs" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy's take is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, transmits the emotion of the disconcertation and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictitious scenes (the impostor team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he gets along pretty well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here it doesn't all go out in such a elegant way (the scene in which the crisis is haunting at Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind his track become crazy).
The weakness of Argo is the discontrol that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, the Affleck film loses a little dramatic, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that's gonna be hard.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omnisscience of secret services can be, it is sufficient.
