The MVRDV architecture study shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently finished "mountain of books" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and at last there's something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a bystander passing the street.
And Stefan Spermon, a IT technician in a large company located near the library, points out: "In addition, the building is nice."
But I wonder why we need a library these days.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
No one gets into those old-fashioned libraries for good, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom city located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having set itself up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this disgraceful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and to copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated armed concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how policy-makers decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a whole master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings at the same time cynical, took the theme with his usual serenity and appeared to the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'. "
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain rises at the planned location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012."
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012."
In this way, the small city without history, which to date had nothing to offer but a post-modern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall after whose white façade one would rather intubate a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a quesera.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the recessed brick floor and the elegant lanterns unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up you can see the park banks, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books, and more books.
"The bookshelves are usually arranged along the facade and in the center a huge dark room is opened which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to turn up the classic spatial configuration and get the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well taken advantage of: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves that assume the functions of wall, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more daily shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a frieze farm, we run into the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a low-millimeter plastic fabric has been used as a basis for holding the roots of the crops.
This is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until it got plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sport slipper.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain we have the reward: from the cafeteria you have not only a fantastic view of the city, but also a tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere at the same time that maintain the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is difficult to believe, given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located in a cross-sectional direction to the glass facade serve to give shade and absorb most of the rays of the sun.
This creates a comfortable inner climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical worker in the Information Technology sector, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there, too.
Chinese traditional medical teacher Cynthia Bogarde has also visited the library. She qualifies the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul."
The reason is that, on the occasion of the opening that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its full file; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," said architect Winy Maas.
"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link to this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if I'm just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved complete success in this discipline, which reigns that in the specialized argot is known as "creating an identity."
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and inculcated he may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
