In a constantly connected world, it's not so bad to get bored a little.
During this year's Thanksgiving parties, I had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on had a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spend half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting the duty-free stores.
But there are more and more academics and child development experts who praise the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it's okay that, both we and our children, we get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since, at present, most of us are connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept the boredom in a good way?
Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, Professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary in Canada, claims, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press, is not so.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
In the walls of Pompeya there are graffiti in Latin on boredom dating from the 1st century AD
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a wide range of ways," says John D. Eastwood, Professor of Psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and putting the idea before a 100-person discussion group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you."
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the care process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can sound terribly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a question of the environment or of the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be their own.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what's really happening to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in the September edition of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading the article of a magazine.
Some groups heard in the next room a full-volume television show that had no relationship, others heard it with the low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear the audio at any time.
The group that heard the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it was hard to concentrate, but they were not sure why and they attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the disruption of attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective pieces in a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not get bored."
"In fact, we now know that moving or doing scribbles, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight it, as they make that person physically more alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stand still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: the delay of a plane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a "boredom trend scale" in the 1980s.
The scale includes issues such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that I'm interested in that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using these scales, researchers have discovered that boys have a more tendency to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, adolescents are a kind of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and his parents between seven and eight times a day through a search.
He discovered that 32 percent of teenagers said he was bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said he was bored when he was not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of the parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said that what he did know was that "adolescence is a period in which boredom reaches its highest levels," largely because both children and adolescents are not given great control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, as, taken to the end, it can cause us to be exposed to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into substance consumption as a method to combat it, as the research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the way the brain has to tell you you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar or cook, that'll satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your son is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to be dosed," says Professor Fenske.
And "that capacity to measure is applied to other situations," he says.
Your son not only learns to entertain himself, but also learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Our objective should be, rather, to be comfortable away from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to be more bored, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate it to something that is worth it," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it is difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise ceases."
