This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has exploited the volcano since 1960 and, never better, its workers, to whom it pays 662 rupees Indonesian (5 cents of euro) for every kilo of sulphur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euro) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in daily life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As it is normal to load 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," Anto explains, who usually carries out three daily ports.
