Despite its penguins, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and both the weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of recharge per chamber that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists to come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for the beasts and not for the people," says Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been in the Kawah Ijin three decades since he left school.
He can raise up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "all he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
