Each week, students explore apocalyptic issues such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the religious professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he had an irresistible hook: The end of the "long countdown" of the Maya Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clung as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what he expected in the next couple of months: The cataclysmic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal precipice that some have called "debitarageddon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-of-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If you analyze what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those with apocalyptic mentality.
And he's not the only teacher who offers courses on the "end of the world" this semester, in theory the last in history.
In Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic issues such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could erupt.
This month the students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they are compared to real-life examples.
"I have tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, have set up a team to teach a course, entitled "The End of the World."
"We do not add '2012' to always have the option to give the course again, in case the world is not over," Restall said.
Despite the "imminent ruin," students must study, generate projects and take final tests.
In Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students with no choice but to work "until the same night the world is supposed to end," Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
"It was saturated in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-average students, which was filled with 35 students.
We received e-mail messages for weeks and weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
The students, for their part, claim that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religious and sociology career student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
The apocalyptic, secular or religious mentality is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of the Psychology and Nursing career, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I've never heard of a class that could teach that," he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed - and much less a teacher - said he believed in the expiry date of December 21.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy and we discredited it in a way," said Julie Zeglen, a senior student at Temple, 21 years old and West Chester.
